6
00:00:22,289 --> 00:00:25,958
narrator: today on "how it's made"...     

7
00:00:25,960 --> 00:00:27,894
throttle bodies.        

8
00:00:27,896 --> 00:00:32,031
♪          

9
00:00:32,033 --> 00:00:33,900
limestone fireplace mantels.  

10
00:00:33,902 --> 00:00:38,170
♪          

11
00:00:38,172 --> 00:00:39,905
candied fruit and fruit jellies.       

12
00:00:39,907 --> 00:00:44,042
♪          

13
00:00:44,044 --> 00:00:46,245
and linen ukuleles.      

14
00:00:46,247 --> 00:00:49,982
♪          

15
00:00:49,984 --> 00:00:52,451
[ sign squeaks ]        

16
00:00:52,453 --> 00:00:56,522
the throttle body is a device that allows the engine     

17
00:00:56,524 --> 00:00:59,325
of a fuel-injected vehicle to breathe.      

18
00:00:59,327 --> 00:01:01,060
pressing on the accelerator pedal     

19
00:01:01,062 --> 00:01:05,598
opens the throttle body's blades
to allow air into the engine. 

20
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:09,201
the greater the airflow, the higher the rpm.      

21
00:01:09,203 --> 00:01:12,471
all the driver has to do is step on the gas.      

22
00:01:12,473 --> 00:01:14,540
♪          

23
00:01:14,542 --> 00:01:17,410
designed for race cars, the throttle body could make  

24
00:01:17,412 --> 00:01:20,546
the difference between winning and losing.      

25
00:01:20,548 --> 00:01:22,548
that's due to the way it delivers the air      

26
00:01:22,550 --> 00:01:25,484
the engine needs for speed.  

27
00:01:25,486 --> 00:01:29,888
making a throttle body starts with this solid aluminum disk. 

28
00:01:29,890 --> 00:01:32,425
a technician mounts it to a machining fixture      

29
00:01:32,427 --> 00:01:35,428
and closes the door.      

30
00:01:35,430 --> 00:01:37,964
computer controlled cutters move in.        

31
00:01:37,966 --> 00:01:42,535
the cutters reduce the thickness
of the disk and contour it.  

32
00:01:42,537 --> 00:01:46,104
they also rough out the shape of four air passageways.    

33
00:01:46,106 --> 00:01:48,507
♪          

34
00:01:48,509 --> 00:01:50,376
then they flip the part over, 

35
00:01:50,378 --> 00:01:55,181
and more cutting tools work on it from the other side.   

36
00:01:55,183 --> 00:01:58,250
the cutters open up the air passageways completely     

37
00:01:58,252 --> 00:02:02,455
and create a hole in the center for a bolt.   

38
00:02:02,457 --> 00:02:04,857
the technician clamps a square chunk of aluminum   

39
00:02:04,859 --> 00:02:06,124
in the fixture,        

40
00:02:06,126 --> 00:02:09,729
and cutters transform it into the main body part.    

41
00:02:09,731 --> 00:02:13,598
this is a computer simulation of the process.        

42
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:16,001
the tools carve four holes to match up          

43
00:02:16,003 --> 00:02:18,070
to the ones on the top piece. 

44
00:02:18,072 --> 00:02:22,208
these holes will hold the throttle mechanisms.    

45
00:02:22,210 --> 00:02:25,144
the transformation takes just minutes.      

46
00:02:25,146 --> 00:02:28,013
♪          

47
00:02:28,015 --> 00:02:30,549
with the parts now electrically charged,     

48
00:02:30,551 --> 00:02:33,018
workers plunge them into a pool of chemicals    

49
00:02:33,020 --> 00:02:34,487
called an etching bath.    

50
00:02:34,489 --> 00:02:37,756
the chemicals gravitate to the electrically charged parts   

51
00:02:37,758 --> 00:02:41,293
and lightly etch the surface. 

52
00:02:41,295 --> 00:02:44,430
a dip in soapy water cleans the parts.       

53
00:02:44,432 --> 00:02:46,632
they are now ready for anodizing,         

54
00:02:46,634 --> 00:02:49,435
a process that will form an anti-corrosion finish    

55
00:02:49,437 --> 00:02:52,437
on the surface.        

56
00:02:52,439 --> 00:02:55,841
in the anodizing bath, an electrical charge causes  

57
00:02:55,843 --> 00:02:59,178
a protective oxide layer to form on the metal,     

58
00:02:59,180 --> 00:03:03,115
and black dye seeps into the pores.     

59
00:03:03,117 --> 00:03:06,919
here are the parts before and after anodizing.      

60
00:03:06,921 --> 00:03:10,322
♪          

61
00:03:10,324 --> 00:03:12,391
a laser then engraves the brand name         

62
00:03:12,393 --> 00:03:15,327
onto the side of the throttle body part.    

63
00:03:15,329 --> 00:03:17,596
the etched aluminum wording stands out           

64
00:03:17,598 --> 00:03:21,200
against the black anodized coating.       

65
00:03:21,202 --> 00:03:24,536
a technician then inserts two stainless steel shafts   

66
00:03:24,538 --> 00:03:27,740
into sealed bearings in holes on the side.     

67
00:03:27,742 --> 00:03:30,542
when turned, the shafts will open and close      

68
00:03:30,544 --> 00:03:34,346
the round throttle blades.   

69
00:03:34,348 --> 00:03:37,816
he installs retaining clips on the shafts.         

70
00:03:37,818 --> 00:03:41,554
this keeps them in place and centers them perfectly.  

71
00:03:41,556 --> 00:03:45,891
but at the same time, they allow
the blades to turn freely.   

72
00:03:45,893 --> 00:03:50,028
♪          

73
00:03:50,030 --> 00:03:55,167
he then screws round blades to the flat part of each shaft.

74
00:03:55,169 --> 00:03:59,038
as the shafts turn, these blades
will move into an open     

75
00:03:59,040 --> 00:04:01,240
or closed position.      

76
00:04:01,242 --> 00:04:02,842
they'll act as valves,     

77
00:04:02,844 --> 00:04:06,378
allowing air into the engine or shutting it off.      

78
00:04:06,380 --> 00:04:10,049
♪          

79
00:04:10,051 --> 00:04:14,720
he attaches a mechanical linkage
to the end of each shaft.   

80
00:04:14,722 --> 00:04:18,057
these linkages will ultimately be connected to a cable    

81
00:04:18,059 --> 00:04:20,793
that runs to the gas pedal.  

82
00:04:20,795 --> 00:04:22,928
when the driver steps on the gas,          

83
00:04:22,930 --> 00:04:25,197
the linkages will turn the shafts,     

84
00:04:25,199 --> 00:04:27,800
and the blades will open and close.      

85
00:04:27,802 --> 00:04:32,271
♪          

86
00:04:32,273 --> 00:04:36,408
he connects the two linkages with a part called a tie bar. 

87
00:04:36,410 --> 00:04:40,279
♪          

88
00:04:40,281 --> 00:04:41,680
now that they're connected,  

89
00:04:41,682 --> 00:04:44,683
the linkages will move together in one action.    

90
00:04:44,685 --> 00:04:49,421
♪          

91
00:04:49,423 --> 00:04:51,690
the technician tests the linkages to confirm    

92
00:04:51,692 --> 00:04:53,759
that they operate smoothly.  

93
00:04:56,096 --> 00:04:59,965
he now places the top part onto the throttle body.    

94
00:04:59,967 --> 00:05:02,768
he applies a thread-lock solution to a bolt,      

95
00:05:02,770 --> 00:05:07,039
which he then inserts in the center of the assembly. 

96
00:05:07,041 --> 00:05:08,974
this is a crucial connection. 

97
00:05:08,976 --> 00:05:12,311
it's what holds the two parts of the throttle body together. 

98
00:05:16,183 --> 00:05:19,551
he secures the center bolt with a threaded insert.    

99
00:05:19,553 --> 00:05:24,990
this insert will also be used to
attach an intake air cleaner. 

100
00:05:24,992 --> 00:05:29,194
this throttle body is now complete.        

101
00:05:29,196 --> 00:05:31,864
workers measure air flow through the throttle body   

102
00:05:31,866 --> 00:05:35,134
using smoke so our camera can photograph it.       

103
00:05:35,136 --> 00:05:37,669
with this measurement, they give the throttle body  

104
00:05:37,671 --> 00:05:39,505
a performance rating.     

105
00:05:41,876 --> 00:05:43,808
a crew installs the throttle body       

106
00:05:43,810 --> 00:05:47,679
between the race car's intake manifold and air filter.

107
00:05:47,681 --> 00:05:49,715
then, they check its function. 

108
00:05:52,153 --> 00:05:56,288
this performance throttle body is now ready to compete.    

109
00:05:56,290 --> 00:05:58,991
♪          

110
00:06:05,833 --> 00:06:10,436
♪          

111
00:06:10,438 --> 00:06:12,704
narrator: for hundreds of years,     

112
00:06:12,706 --> 00:06:14,873
stone carvers have skillfully sculpted      

113
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:18,911
blocks of solid stone into ornate fireplace mantels. 

114
00:06:18,913 --> 00:06:21,647
a work of art with an imposing presence,     

115
00:06:21,649 --> 00:06:24,850
a stone mantel is the decorative
centerpiece of a room.     

116
00:06:24,852 --> 00:06:26,985
whether or not there's a fire burning,        

117
00:06:26,987 --> 00:06:30,121
it creates a warm ambience.  

118
00:06:30,123 --> 00:06:31,857
♪          

119
00:06:31,859 --> 00:06:35,094
modern-day stone carvers carry on a trade passed down  

120
00:06:35,096 --> 00:06:36,729
through the centuries,     

121
00:06:36,731 --> 00:06:39,431
crafting limestone fireplace mantels       

122
00:06:39,433 --> 00:06:42,801
that exude old-world elegance. 

123
00:06:42,803 --> 00:06:45,870
artisans sketch out a creative design,       

124
00:06:45,872 --> 00:06:50,141
then produce a technical drawing
and 3-d model on a computer.  

125
00:06:50,143 --> 00:06:53,946
this particular mantel, carved from beige limestone,  

126
00:06:53,948 --> 00:06:56,948
will feature a medallion of red sandstone.       

127
00:06:56,950 --> 00:06:59,952
the red medallion will be set into the keystone,       

128
00:06:59,954 --> 00:07:02,855
which is the central block of what's called the lintel,  

129
00:07:02,857 --> 00:07:04,956
the horizontal part of the mantel.         

130
00:07:04,958 --> 00:07:07,025
after finalizing the measurements,       

131
00:07:07,027 --> 00:07:10,028
the artisans lay down a sheet of thick white plastic     

132
00:07:10,030 --> 00:07:12,231
and draw the mantel's overall shape,         

133
00:07:12,233 --> 00:07:15,500
as seen from the front, in its actual dimensions.   

134
00:07:15,502 --> 00:07:18,304
the mantel will be composed of several parts        

135
00:07:18,306 --> 00:07:21,907
so they will also mark the joints where those parts meet. 

136
00:07:23,978 --> 00:07:27,046
using this pattern, they cut a clear plastic template    

137
00:07:27,048 --> 00:07:30,783
for each part.         

138
00:07:30,785 --> 00:07:33,519
the artisans use a combination of traditional         

139
00:07:33,521 --> 00:07:36,055
and modern stone-carving tools.

140
00:07:38,659 --> 00:07:42,995
first, for each part, they use an automated diamond-blade saw 

141
00:07:42,997 --> 00:07:44,930
to cut a block to size.    

142
00:07:44,932 --> 00:07:48,667
♪          

143
00:07:48,669 --> 00:07:52,004
they then measure and mark where they need to remove stone

144
00:07:52,006 --> 00:07:55,073
to shape the block to the basic profile.     

145
00:07:55,075 --> 00:08:02,948
♪          

146
00:08:02,950 --> 00:08:06,018
the artisan gradually removes that portion of stone     

147
00:08:06,020 --> 00:08:09,354
with a hammer and different types of chisels.

148
00:08:09,356 --> 00:08:13,425
limestone can be hard like marble, or soft like chalk.  

149
00:08:13,427 --> 00:08:15,026
there's less margin for error 

150
00:08:15,028 --> 00:08:17,763
when carving softer limestone, like this,     

151
00:08:17,765 --> 00:08:21,033
because every strike of the hammer removes more stone   

152
00:08:21,035 --> 00:08:24,970
than the same strike on a hard limestone would.   

153
00:08:24,972 --> 00:08:27,972
this tool, designed for soft limestone,  

154
00:08:27,974 --> 00:08:32,844
wears away the surface like  
a plane does to a piece of wood.

155
00:08:32,846 --> 00:08:36,114
once the artisan has removed all the excess stone,     

156
00:08:36,116 --> 00:08:39,651
he checks that the surface is level.     

157
00:08:39,653 --> 00:08:42,454
then, in the side of the block,
he traces a template      

158
00:08:42,456 --> 00:08:44,322
for the profile.        

159
00:08:44,324 --> 00:08:46,325
this block will become the keystone          

160
00:08:46,327 --> 00:08:50,595
for the horizontal part of the mantel.      

161
00:08:50,597 --> 00:08:54,599
he measures out and marks the center of the keystone... 

162
00:08:54,601 --> 00:08:59,738
♪          

163
00:08:59,740 --> 00:09:03,475
...then centers the medallion and traces it.         

164
00:09:03,477 --> 00:09:07,112
he'll draw the remainder of the keystone's design freehand.

165
00:09:09,416 --> 00:09:11,216
the design is symmetrical,   

166
00:09:11,218 --> 00:09:14,486
so the artisan draws on one side of the center line,

167
00:09:14,488 --> 00:09:16,955
traces his drawing onto the clear plastic     

168
00:09:16,957 --> 00:09:18,623
to make a template,      

169
00:09:18,625 --> 00:09:21,160
then flips the template onto the
other side of the center line 

170
00:09:21,162 --> 00:09:24,430
to trace the same design in mirror image.        

171
00:09:24,432 --> 00:09:29,968
♪          

172
00:09:29,970 --> 00:09:34,372
he begins removing stone with a hammer and roughing tools.  

173
00:09:34,374 --> 00:09:38,110
first, he breaks off big chunks
with a chipper.        

174
00:09:38,112 --> 00:09:42,915
he works his way down to just above the pencil line.     

175
00:09:42,917 --> 00:09:47,920
then, with a finer tooth chisel,
he removes the last bit.    

176
00:09:47,922 --> 00:09:50,589
then he switches to finishing tools.      

177
00:09:50,591 --> 00:09:53,725
he mounts chisels of varying widths on an air hammer    

178
00:09:53,727 --> 00:09:56,628
to remove a precise, even layer of stone.      

179
00:09:58,732 --> 00:10:01,400
working on the more complex details,        

180
00:10:01,402 --> 00:10:03,669
he uses a combination square  

181
00:10:03,671 --> 00:10:07,272
to mark a consistent height across the keystone.      

182
00:10:07,274 --> 00:10:09,608
every detail of the keystone profile      

183
00:10:09,610 --> 00:10:12,144
must align with the same profile detail    

184
00:10:12,146 --> 00:10:14,613
of the lentil pieces on either side of it.     

185
00:10:17,017 --> 00:10:19,951
once he has finished      
the entire profile of the piece,

186
00:10:19,953 --> 00:10:24,690
he sands the surface smooth and brushes away the dust.   

187
00:10:27,895 --> 00:10:29,695
now the artisan turns his attention         

188
00:10:29,697 --> 00:10:33,164
to the keystone's ornate sculpt design.         

189
00:10:33,166 --> 00:10:36,301
with fine, flat, and pointed chisels,      

190
00:10:36,303 --> 00:10:39,104
he removes the stone around his pencil lines    

191
00:10:39,106 --> 00:10:42,174
until the design he drew emerges.        

192
00:10:42,176 --> 00:10:46,578
♪          

193
00:10:46,580 --> 00:10:49,047
by switching to a sculptor's rasp,       

194
00:10:49,049 --> 00:10:51,650
he smoothes all the rough edges.

195
00:10:53,787 --> 00:10:56,688
he checks the fit of the red sandstone medallion      

196
00:10:56,690 --> 00:10:57,856
and glues it in.        

197
00:10:57,858 --> 00:11:01,460
♪          

198
00:11:01,462 --> 00:11:04,463
once the artisan finishes sculpting all the parts,    

199
00:11:04,465 --> 00:11:05,931
he lays them on the pattern  

200
00:11:05,933 --> 00:11:09,067
to make sure all the dimensions are perfect.  

201
00:11:09,069 --> 00:11:13,338
on installation day, he mounts the mantel, piece by piece,  

202
00:11:13,340 --> 00:11:16,175
around the fireplace.     

203
00:11:23,484 --> 00:11:27,886
♪          

204
00:11:27,888 --> 00:11:30,322
narrator: candied fruit and fruit jellies       

205
00:11:30,324 --> 00:11:32,023
are middle eastern in origin  

206
00:11:32,025 --> 00:11:34,893
and spread to europe around the 12th century.    

207
00:11:34,895 --> 00:11:37,095
this region of france has been producing them    

208
00:11:37,097 --> 00:11:39,097
since the 15th century.    

209
00:11:39,099 --> 00:11:41,633
when wars blocked access to cane sugar,         

210
00:11:41,635 --> 00:11:44,503
fruit farmers began planting sugar beets      

211
00:11:44,505 --> 00:11:47,906
to preserve this confectionery tradition.    

212
00:11:47,908 --> 00:11:50,308
♪          

213
00:11:50,310 --> 00:11:53,712
this company in france has been
catering to people's sweet tooth

214
00:11:53,714 --> 00:11:56,447
since 1880 with its gift boxes 

215
00:11:56,449 --> 00:12:01,987
containing traditional candied fruit and fruit jellies.    

216
00:12:01,989 --> 00:12:05,857
to make candied fruit, a master
confectioner boils fresh fruit 

217
00:12:05,859 --> 00:12:08,860
for many hours to soften the fibers.     

218
00:12:08,862 --> 00:12:12,797
this process will later help sugar to penetrate the fruit. 

219
00:12:12,799 --> 00:12:16,534
he pokes the fruit to see if it's ready.         

220
00:12:16,536 --> 00:12:19,938
boiling time varies from 1 hour for apricots    

221
00:12:19,940 --> 00:12:22,341
to 8 hours for chestnuts.   

222
00:12:22,343 --> 00:12:26,545
citrus fruits are sliced before boiling.        

223
00:12:26,547 --> 00:12:29,481
after boiling, the more fragile types of fruit,    

224
00:12:29,483 --> 00:12:32,618
such as apricots, pears and clementines,     

225
00:12:32,620 --> 00:12:36,955
go into large hot-air dehydrators for up to 3 weeks. 

226
00:12:36,957 --> 00:12:39,491
every day, the master confectioner replaces     

227
00:12:39,493 --> 00:12:42,160
the evaporated water with sugar syrup,       

228
00:12:42,162 --> 00:12:46,031
which concentrates over time. 

229
00:12:46,033 --> 00:12:49,167
for less fragile fruits, the technique is different.  

230
00:12:49,169 --> 00:12:53,438
workers heat them in vats of sugar syrup for about 10 days. 

231
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:57,075
the moisture evaporates, and the syrup concentrates.  

232
00:12:59,313 --> 00:13:02,380
the factory sells whole candied fruits      

233
00:13:02,382 --> 00:13:04,449
like this collection of clementines,        

234
00:13:04,451 --> 00:13:07,185
apricots, pears, figs, and plums,           

235
00:13:07,187 --> 00:13:09,054
to gourmet food shops,     

236
00:13:09,056 --> 00:13:11,856
which sell them by the piece or in elegant,         

237
00:13:11,858 --> 00:13:14,125
private-label gift boxes.   

238
00:13:14,127 --> 00:13:19,531
♪          

239
00:13:19,533 --> 00:13:21,666
whole candied fruit are also popular        

240
00:13:21,668 --> 00:13:25,336
for designing edible arrangements.      

241
00:13:25,338 --> 00:13:28,606
making fruit jellies is a different process.    

242
00:13:28,608 --> 00:13:30,942
the recipe combines fruit pulp,

243
00:13:30,944 --> 00:13:33,344
making up more than 50 percent of the mixture,   

244
00:13:33,346 --> 00:13:36,280
with powdered sugar, liquid glucose,        

245
00:13:36,282 --> 00:13:38,016
a form of plant sugar,     

246
00:13:38,018 --> 00:13:40,619
pectin to make the mixture gelatinous,    

247
00:13:40,621 --> 00:13:43,221
and natural fruit flavoring.  

248
00:13:43,223 --> 00:13:45,757
a worker boils down the mix for a half hour        

249
00:13:45,759 --> 00:13:47,492
to concentrate the sugar,   

250
00:13:47,494 --> 00:13:50,027
then adds more fruit flavoring.

251
00:13:50,029 --> 00:13:52,164
as the mix continues to cook, 

252
00:13:52,166 --> 00:13:55,500
she draws samples to measure the sugar content.       

253
00:13:55,502 --> 00:13:57,168
she does this until the mix  

254
00:13:57,170 --> 00:14:01,840
hits its target concentration of 78 percent.  

255
00:14:01,842 --> 00:14:05,510
♪          

256
00:14:05,512 --> 00:14:07,846
another worker pours the batch from the pot     

257
00:14:07,848 --> 00:14:09,381
into a large pitcher,     

258
00:14:09,383 --> 00:14:12,284
then into a square stainless steel mold.     

259
00:14:14,455 --> 00:14:17,455
it takes the jelly a day to set.

260
00:14:17,457 --> 00:14:20,592
once set, a worker removes it from the mold --        

261
00:14:20,594 --> 00:14:22,527
this one's a different flavor --     

262
00:14:22,529 --> 00:14:27,465
and coats it with crystallized sugar to preserve it.     

263
00:14:27,467 --> 00:14:30,202
the worker then lays the jelly square on cutter   

264
00:14:30,204 --> 00:14:32,203
the company calls a guitar   

265
00:14:32,205 --> 00:14:35,874
because its steel wires look like guitar strings.   

266
00:14:35,876 --> 00:14:39,811
the wires cut once in each direction to make cubes.    

267
00:14:39,813 --> 00:14:43,815
then, another worker applies a second coating of sugar.   

268
00:14:43,817 --> 00:14:46,551
in addition to this small-batch production,    

269
00:14:46,553 --> 00:14:48,953
the factory has one automated machine,   

270
00:14:48,955 --> 00:14:50,122
which makes fruit jellies   

271
00:14:50,124 --> 00:14:53,225
in a variety of geometric or fruit shapes        

272
00:14:53,227 --> 00:14:55,426
created by templates made of plaster.        

273
00:14:55,428 --> 00:14:58,362
♪          

274
00:14:58,364 --> 00:15:02,634
this process is much faster than the handmade approach.  

275
00:15:02,636 --> 00:15:07,305
first, the machine makes a bed of starch.     

276
00:15:07,307 --> 00:15:09,975
then it presses the plaster form into the bed 

277
00:15:09,977 --> 00:15:12,577
to create mold cavities.    

278
00:15:12,579 --> 00:15:17,115
♪          

279
00:15:17,117 --> 00:15:18,917
the next station fills the cavities          

280
00:15:18,919 --> 00:15:21,519
with hot liquid fruit jelly.  

281
00:15:21,521 --> 00:15:25,390
then, the molds are set aside for a day.    

282
00:15:25,392 --> 00:15:30,462
the starch absorbs the residual
moisture as the jelly sets.  

283
00:15:30,464 --> 00:15:32,997
the next day, workers load the molds     

284
00:15:32,999 --> 00:15:34,799
on top of the same machine,  

285
00:15:34,801 --> 00:15:37,802
which flips them to dump out the jellies.          

286
00:15:37,804 --> 00:15:41,273
the jellies tumble down a vibrating conveyor belt.   

287
00:15:41,275 --> 00:15:44,742
the starch shakes off with each bounce.       

288
00:15:44,744 --> 00:15:46,677
then they pass under a spinning brush,    

289
00:15:46,679 --> 00:15:50,415
which removes any remaining starch.     

290
00:15:50,417 --> 00:15:53,351
the conveyor moves them into a rotating drum,     

291
00:15:53,353 --> 00:15:55,287
which showers them with sugar. 

292
00:15:57,224 --> 00:16:00,424
on the packaging line, a slow conveyor belt moves   

293
00:16:00,426 --> 00:16:04,095
retail boxes in front of a row of workers. 

294
00:16:04,097 --> 00:16:07,499
each worker is responsible for a single flavor.      

295
00:16:07,501 --> 00:16:09,834
while placing the required number of fruit jellies    

296
00:16:09,836 --> 00:16:10,836
in the box,          

297
00:16:10,838 --> 00:16:13,905
she also performs a quality control check,    

298
00:16:13,907 --> 00:16:17,241
removing and replacing any that are misshapen.    

299
00:16:17,243 --> 00:16:20,044
this ensures that these traditional fruit jellies   

300
00:16:20,046 --> 00:16:22,481
look as good as they taste.  

301
00:16:29,656 --> 00:16:34,192
♪          

302
00:16:34,194 --> 00:16:36,528
narrator: linen is believed to be    

303
00:16:36,530 --> 00:16:39,464
the oldest of woven textiles. 

304
00:16:39,466 --> 00:16:43,735
but for the making of ukuleles,
it's definitely a new material.

305
00:16:43,737 --> 00:16:45,536
infused with resin,      

306
00:16:45,538 --> 00:16:49,540
linen can actually be molded into a solid ukulele      

307
00:16:49,542 --> 00:16:52,577
that has a look and sound that's similar to wood.    

308
00:16:54,147 --> 00:16:55,880
♪          

309
00:16:55,882 --> 00:17:00,151
linen may seem to be an unlikely
material for making ukuleles, 

310
00:17:00,153 --> 00:17:03,187
but these instruments are proof
that the fabric can be used  

311
00:17:03,189 --> 00:17:07,358
for more than just drapes and tablecloths.    

312
00:17:07,360 --> 00:17:09,694
following a computer-aided design,    

313
00:17:09,696 --> 00:17:12,898
workers cut pattern pieces from linen fabric,       

314
00:17:12,900 --> 00:17:17,702
infused with plant resin and with protective liners.  

315
00:17:17,704 --> 00:17:19,771
after peeling off the liners, 

316
00:17:19,773 --> 00:17:24,375
a technician layers the linen pieces in a ukulele mold.   

317
00:17:24,377 --> 00:17:27,979
the resin has given the fabric a clay-like consistency,    

318
00:17:27,981 --> 00:17:31,916
so it can be easily shaped to the mold's curves.     

319
00:17:31,918 --> 00:17:34,886
he layers 65 linen pieces in total.        

320
00:17:36,923 --> 00:17:39,657
he drapes a nylon fabric over the linen         

321
00:17:39,659 --> 00:17:41,526
and tucks it into the crevices.

322
00:17:41,528 --> 00:17:44,062
the fabric will ultimately contain the resin       

323
00:17:44,064 --> 00:17:46,665
when it's heated and liquefied.

324
00:17:46,667 --> 00:17:50,268
polyester batting in the center
will soak up excess resin   

325
00:17:50,270 --> 00:17:52,671
during baking.         

326
00:17:52,673 --> 00:17:55,940
he cooks the linen layers for several hours.       

327
00:17:55,942 --> 00:17:59,210
the resin in the fabric subsequently liquifies     

328
00:17:59,212 --> 00:18:02,614
and finally hardens, fusing the layers together,  

329
00:18:02,616 --> 00:18:06,818
to create a solid ukulele body, next and head.      

330
00:18:06,820 --> 00:18:08,887
after reinforcing the neck,  

331
00:18:08,889 --> 00:18:13,625
a computerized router trims the entire ukulele body.    

332
00:18:13,627 --> 00:18:16,161
another router trims the sound board,        

333
00:18:16,163 --> 00:18:17,762
which is the resonant part   

334
00:18:17,764 --> 00:18:20,899
that serves as the front of the instrument.       

335
00:18:20,901 --> 00:18:23,568
it, too, has been molded from linen material.      

336
00:18:23,570 --> 00:18:26,905
♪          

337
00:18:26,907 --> 00:18:30,775
a technician pipes epoxy glue along the rim of the body   

338
00:18:30,777 --> 00:18:32,443
to attach the soundboard,   

339
00:18:32,445 --> 00:18:35,513
which is being reinforced with carbon fiber       

340
00:18:35,515 --> 00:18:38,984
and a plastic liner applied for the front to protect it  

341
00:18:38,986 --> 00:18:40,986
during this stage of fabrication.        

342
00:18:40,988 --> 00:18:44,088
♪          

343
00:18:44,090 --> 00:18:48,926
he glues a front plate     
to the headstock of the ukulele.

344
00:18:48,928 --> 00:18:52,263
he then places the ukulele in a fixture.         

345
00:18:52,265 --> 00:18:55,867
he clamps the fixture together to keep the parts in position 

346
00:18:55,869 --> 00:19:00,805
as the glue hardens for 24 hours.         

347
00:19:00,807 --> 00:19:03,875
he props up the headstock with a block of wood      

348
00:19:03,877 --> 00:19:09,013
and uses a separate clamp to keep the assembly tight.  

349
00:19:09,015 --> 00:19:12,349
a router carves an opening in the soundboard.       

350
00:19:12,351 --> 00:19:14,953
this sound hole with allow the instrument      

351
00:19:14,955 --> 00:19:19,023
to project music more efficiently.       

352
00:19:19,025 --> 00:19:23,962
the router also drills tuning holes in the head plate.

353
00:19:23,964 --> 00:19:27,298
another member of the team now applies a wood stain    

354
00:19:27,300 --> 00:19:31,035
to the linen composite surface.

355
00:19:31,037 --> 00:19:33,638
this gives it a more uniform finish.     

356
00:19:37,177 --> 00:19:39,511
the next part is the finger board,      

357
00:19:39,513 --> 00:19:42,714
made of a wood fiber and plastic composite.     

358
00:19:42,716 --> 00:19:45,583
another technician hammers nickel silver frets      

359
00:19:45,585 --> 00:19:47,819
into the fingerboard's slots. 

360
00:19:50,123 --> 00:19:55,593
he then clips the ends to make them flush to the fingerboard. 

361
00:19:55,595 --> 00:20:00,198
he files the ends to make them smooth to the touch.      

362
00:20:00,200 --> 00:20:04,802
he then glues the fingerboard to the ukulele neck.      

363
00:20:04,804 --> 00:20:07,872
the technician installs the bridge on the soundboard. 

364
00:20:07,874 --> 00:20:09,474
using a special fixture,    

365
00:20:09,476 --> 00:20:11,543
he clamps the fingerboard and bridge           

366
00:20:11,545 --> 00:20:15,447
to the instrument to apply pressure while the glue dries. 

367
00:20:17,550 --> 00:20:20,951
it takes another 24 hours for the glue to set.      

368
00:20:20,953 --> 00:20:25,489
♪          

369
00:20:25,491 --> 00:20:29,360
the next day, a technician   
applies an adhesive-backed label

370
00:20:29,362 --> 00:20:31,228
with the serial number printed on it         

371
00:20:31,230 --> 00:20:33,564
to the inside of the ukulele. 

372
00:20:33,566 --> 00:20:38,703
♪          

373
00:20:38,705 --> 00:20:41,172
he inserts tuning pegs into holes drilled       

374
00:20:41,174 --> 00:20:44,642
into the headstock.      

375
00:20:44,644 --> 00:20:48,046
he secures the pegs with bolts at the back of the headstock  

376
00:20:48,048 --> 00:20:50,615
and tightens the bolts with a nut driver.       

377
00:20:53,052 --> 00:20:56,854
then he runs strings from the bridge to the tuning pegs 

378
00:20:56,856 --> 00:20:59,124
and knots them to hold them in place.      

379
00:20:59,126 --> 00:21:02,794
♪          

380
00:21:02,796 --> 00:21:05,063
he turns the tuners to pull the strings      

381
00:21:05,065 --> 00:21:06,931
to a specific tension,     

382
00:21:06,933 --> 00:21:10,935
and this linen-composite ukulele
is ready for a show.      

383
00:21:10,937 --> 00:21:17,008
♪          

